    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Endangered Treasures</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Matthew A Selig letter on Sept 5 article cites damage caused by opening caves to human visits; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Beautiful formations like stalactites are not the only significant formations in caves (''Glories of Underworld Are Under Siege,'' Sept. 5). Breakdown piles, stream sediments, and mud deposits are also important to karst researchers. A site like Kartchner Caverns in Arizona, with its two man-made entrances, 1,100 feet of concrete tunnels, 1,225 feet of trails, electric lighting and misting systems, gets significantly damaged long before the first tourist visits.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Beautiful formations like stalactites are not the only significant formations in caves (''Glories of Underworld Are Under Siege,'' Sept. 5). Breakdown piles, stream sediments, and mud deposits are also important to karst researchers. A site like Kartchner Caverns in Arizona, with its two man-made entrances, 1,100 feet of concrete tunnels, 1,225 feet of trails, electric lighting and misting systems, gets significantly damaged long before the first tourist visits.</p>
        <p>A newly discovered cave shows signs of impact after the first visit of humans. There is no such thing as ''no-impact caving.''</p>
        <p>MATTHEW A. SELIG  Indianapolis</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
